# Planner Guidance

This file contains guidance on planning and writing instructions. After each phase, a phase planner decides whether to proceed to the next segment or add another phase, allowing the plan to adapt based on what actually happened.

## Guidance on Segment Size/Scope

When decomposing tasks, aim to break the work into reasonably self-contained segments. Separate relatively distinct focus areas/sub-objectives into different segments so each segment can stay focused.

Key considerations:
- **Favor more segments over fewer**: Having many segments is acceptable, especially for larger research projects. More segments help keep the AI focused.
- **Context rot**: AI agents sometimes decline in performance over long sessions or when handling many complex things simultaneously, so breaking into more segments helps manage this.
- **Dependencies**: If parts of the work have minimal interdependence, separate them into distinct segments.
- **Natural boundaries**: Look for obvious segment transitions (e.g., "initial investigation" vs "implementation" vs "testing" vs "analysis").

Good segment sizes:
- Doing a de-risking segment of a project (e.g., initial prompting-only experiments that can be relatively easily done)
- Building additional datasets (and then evaluating on these)
- Running a certain class of follow-up experiments
- Running experiments to investigate some component of the overall task/project/tool

Segments that are too small:
- "Write function X" (way too small)
- "Fix bug on line 42" (way too small)

Segments that are too large:
- "Do everything" (defeats the purpose)
- Segments with multiple distinct self-contained tasks that could reasonably be separated

## Misc

You can message prior phase planners if you later need information from them about their decisions or what happened in their phase. You should message them if you end up being unclear on what happened or why some decision was made.

In addition to doing more work within a given segment (by adding another phase), you may also add or adjust segments based on how things go. E.g., after seeing how things went, you can add additional segments (to the end or some other place after the current segment), remove segments, or change how the remaining work is decomposed into segments.

When adding or removing segments, you should shift the numbering of later segments accordingly. (E.g., if you want to skip/remove what used to be segment 3, you should make what used to be segment 4 be segment 3, etc.)

## Instructions Guidance

It's fine if the instructions for each phase of the plan are long and detailed. Instructions must be detailed enough for the agent to complete the work autonomously. Generally lean in the direction of additional detail and information. But, don't be unnecessarily specific in cases where it would be better to leave flexibility for the agent.

You should make sure that instructions always include a good explanation of the motivation/objectives for the overall project. Generally, the instructions should aim to make it clear both what to do and why.

The worker agent for the next phase will start from the full directory state from the prior phase (git repo, other untracked files). For phases after the initial phase (segment 0, phase 0), some text will automatically be added to the actual instructions shown to the worker telling it that it is continuing a broader task/project and should review relevant files in the directory (write-ups, etc.). Your instructions for phases after the initial phase should include relevant context about what happened in prior phases if there is brief helpful context that isn't immediately gained by reading the relevant write-up files.

Your instructions for each phase must be self-contained. That is, they shouldn't reference other files you have in this directory or instructions for earlier phases/segments as the agent won't have access to these. However, the agent will have access to OVERALL_PLAN.md in its directory and will be told about this file, so you can reference it in your phase instructions if this would be useful. (You generally shouldn't depend on the agent reading OVERALL_PLAN.md; instead include relevant information in your instructions.)

# Output Format

Instruction files have the naming convention INSTRUCTIONS_SEGMENT_X_PHASE_Y.md where X is the segment and Y is the phase (both 0 indexed).

Each instruction file should have this format:
```markdown
---
name: "short_phase_name"
description: "Short description of this phase (1-2 sentences)"
---

# Instructions

Your detailed instructions for this phase in markdown formatting.
```

Both fields in the YAML frontmatter are required:
- **name**: A short, underscore-separated name suitable for use in filenames. Each phase (overall, not just within a segment) must have a unique name.
- **description**: A human-readable description of the phase (1-2 sentences).

## Git Usage

Your working directory is a git repo. Commit after updating or adding files.
